{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Research is a foundation of evidence-based practice in SLP.",
    "AI is accelerating research by automating literature reviews (e.g., using tools like Rayyan), and analyzing large datasets.",
    "Tools developed by organizations such as OpenAI (Meyer et al., 2023) and Anthropic (Anthropic, 2025) are already being used to explore complex questions in neuroscience and language processing.",
    "Numerous recent studies have already employed AI-based approaches.",
    "Such studies include predicting dementia from spontaneous speech using large language models (Agbavor & Liang, 2022), predicting developmental language disorders from rhythmic anticipation in children (Beccaluva et al., 2024), forecasting post-stroke patient performance (Billot et al., 2022), detecting sound production (Carl et al., 2024), identifying Parkinson's disease from speech (Escobar-Grisales et al., 2023), classifying aphasia and primary progressive aphasia using connected speech (Fromm et al., 2022; Rezaii et al., 2024), conducting language sample analysis (Lammert et al., 2025), predicting long-term developmental outcomes from early language data (Armstrong et al., 2018), modeling generalization of treated sounds (Benway & Preston, 2024), generating low-cost visual stimuli for individuals with aphasia (Pierce, 2024b) and explaining paraphasias in aphasia (Zavaleta et al., 2025)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Tools developed by organizations such as OpenAI (Meyer et al., 2023) and Anthropic (Anthropic, 2025) are already being used to explore complex questions in neuroscience and language processing.",
    "Such studies include predicting dementia from spontaneous speech using large language models (Agbavor & Liang, 2022), predicting developmental language disorders from rhythmic anticipation in children (Beccaluva et al., 2024), forecasting post-stroke patient performance (Billot et al., 2022), detecting sound production (Carl et al., 2024), identifying Parkinson's disease from speech (Escobar-Grisales et al., 2023), classifying aphasia and primary progressive aphasia using connected speech (Fromm et al., 2022; Rezaii et al., 2024), conducting language sample analysis (Lammert et al., 2025), predicting long-term developmental outcomes from early language data (Armstrong et al., 2018), modeling generalization of treated sounds (Benway & Preston, 2024), generating low-cost visual stimuli for individuals with aphasia (Pierce, 2024b) and explaining paraphasias in aphasia (Zavaleta et al., 2025)."
